ce:section.ce:para:
To investigate the mechanism of CQDRes in reducing virulence factors production, the transcriptome technology was adopted. A sum of 20.89 Gb clean data were obtained. The data from volcanic map (Fig. 4
                        A) and PCA (Fig. 4B) showed DEGs compared between DMSO and CQDRes-treated groups. GO functional enrichment analysis indicated that all DEGs were divided into three categories: cellular component, molecular function, and biological process, consisting of 15, 8, and 17 subcategories, respectively (Fig. 4C). Metabolic process, cellular process, catalytic activity, and binding were the main modules of DEGs distribution. For cellular component, the most vital ones were cell part and membrane. To further explore the biological function and pathway in which DEGs involved, KEGG enrichment was adopted. The first 20 different pathways were used to sort out crucial genes in the KEGG enrichment pathway (Fig. 4D). Based on this result, 35 genes were chose as important genes related to the measured phenotypic data of virulence factors production and biofilm formation (Table 1
                        ).

The proteomic differences in bacterial cells exposed to CQDRes were systematically investigated by TMT. A total of 118 DEPs were assigned in the Res-treated group while 392 DEPs in the CQDRes-treated group compared with the DMSO-treated group. For the CQDRes-treated samples, a sum of 108 proteins were notably up-regulated and 284 proteins notably down-regulated (Fig. 6
                        A). GO enrichment analysis indicated that signal-organism process and integral component of membrane were the leading modules of DEPs distribution (Fig. 6B). To further explore the biological function and pathway in which DEPs involved, KEGG analysis was adopted. The first 20 different pathways were employed to sort out crucial proteins in the KEGG pathway (Fig. 6C). Based on this result, 24 proteins were chose as important proteins related to the measured phenotypic data of virulence factors production and biofilm formation (Table 2
                        ). The data from Table 2 also indicated that the DEPs in the CQDRes-treated group were different from those in the Res-treated group. For example, PqsB, PqsC, PqsD, PqsE, and PqsH were differentially expressed with CQDRes treatment. However, these proteins were not differentially expressed after treatment with Res. Maybe it is the disruption of pqs system that result in the enhanced anti-virulence activity of CQDRes.
